                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.002/218: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan (<persName type="from"
                        >Grew</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-09-18T16:00:00+09:00"
                            >September 18, 1933—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 18—5:32 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>144. At my initial reception today by the new Minister for Foreign Affairs<note
                        n="21" xml:id="d769fn21">Koki Hirota, formerly Japanese Ambassador in the
                        Soviet Union.</note> he said that his principal preoccupation while in
                    office would be the development of better relations with the United States and
                    that this in fact was the primary reason for his having accepted the appointment
                    which had come to him as a complete surprise.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
